Actions.Text:
Unix Time
Traditional timestamp, aka â€˜Epoch Timeâ€™, â€˜Unix Epochâ€™ or â€˜POSIX Timeâ€™. 
Starts at 1970-01-01 and covers 1902 to 2038 with a precision of 1 second.
Cocoa Time
OS X Reference Time. 
Starts at 2001-01-01 (begin of the 3rd millennium) and covers 3000 BC to 7000 AD with a precision of sub-milliseconds. (For convenience, implemented with 1-second precision in this macro.)

More timestamps

Representation
Decimal
Base-10 representation (0â€“9). 
Default and most used; long; recognized by all date tools; almost human-readable.
Hexadecimal
Base-16 representation (0â€“9, Aâ€“F). 
More compact than decimal; less human-readable; recognized by some date tools.
Hexatrigesimal
Base-36 representation (0â€“9, Aâ€“Z). 
The most compact; less human-readable; not recognized by most date tools.

Binary
Base-2 representation (0â€“1). 
Least compact, not very useful for timestamps; ugly and boring to look at; for lovers of 1 and 0. ðŸ¤“
